{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782958624,"nonce":"+WJ1G5myVQE5Thf9C5x9oqt9s8k=","kind":"spec","title":"kref good-CLI-defaults checks \u0026 ingest discoverability — design","content_type":"text/markdown"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782958624,"nonce":"oEyJ6OMGDT8/qknNYpktJV68osA=","body":"# kref good-CLI-defaults checks \u0026 ingest discoverability — design\n\n**Date:** 2026-06-25\n**Status:** approved (brainstorming → ready for implementation plan)\n**Scope:** Two documentation/ergonomics changes, plus a small example\nconsistency fix. (1) Add a \"good CLI defaults\" checks cluster to\n`CRANKY_PROMPT.md`, the cranky-user review prompt. (2) Make `ingest` the\ndiscoverable headline of the standard workflow, and finish the read-only\nmost-recent-default examples. **No command semantics change.** The deeper\n\"living link / reconcile\" idea is deferred to its own spec.\n\n## 1. Context\n\nThe prior `feat/cli-help-defaults` work added actionable arg errors, `--help`\n`Example:` blocks, and a most-recent default for the read-only inspection\ncommands (`show`, `log`, `diff`, `links`, `tree`). This follow-up does two\nthings that fell out of reviewing and discussing that work:\n\n- Captures the **review heuristics** for those default/guidance patterns so the\n  cranky-user review prompt checks for them on any CLI.\n- Closes a **discoverability gap**: the 90% path for this tool is `ingest`\n  (point kref at markdown files or directories), not `add` (a manual one-off),\n  but nothing in the help surface makes that obvious.\n\n`ingest` is genuinely distinct from `add` and must stay its own verb:\n\n- It writes a `kref-id` trailer back into the source file (`internal/bridge/\n  bridge.go:69` `withMarker`) so re-ingest is idempotent\n  (`bridge.go:98-99`: unchanged file = no-op, changed file = update).\n- It fans out over N paths / directory trees (`IngestPaths`, `--skip-missing`,\n  per-file results, partial-failure exit code at `cmd/kref/commands.go:314`).\n- `add` is a one-shot composer from flags and never touches the filesystem.\n\nThe file↔entry binding already exists end to end — the trailer is written on\ningest and read by path-addressing (`bridge.go:55` `IDFromFile`, used by\n`resolveArg`), and re-sync already happens operationally via the post-commit\nhook (`internal/hooks/hooks.go`). So the gap is discoverability, not capability.\n\nTwo adjacent design directions were considered and **rejected for this scope**:\n\n- *Merging `ingest` into `add`.* Overloads `add`'s contract (1-entry-from-flags\n  vs N-files-with-write-back) and would make an innocuous-sounding command\n  silently mutate user files — the very least-surprise violation we are adding a\n  check against.\n- *A cross-cutting \"sync\" attribute/flag.* The verb `sync` already means \"sync\n  tiers with their git remotes\" (`commands.go:630`); reusing it for file\n  mirroring collides. A per-entry \"keep synced with local file\" attribute is\n  inherently machine-local, but entries are shareable across machines via the\n  `shared` tier — so it cannot live in shared entry state without becoming\n  misleading. Deferred to a separate spec (see §6).\n\n## 2. Goals / non-goals\n\n**Goals**\n\n- `CRANKY_PROMPT.md` gains a checks cluster for good CLI defaults (the eight\n  checks in §3.1), phrased as findings to match the prompt's existing voice.\n- `ingest` is the obvious headline of the standard workflow: walkthrough\n  examples that teach idempotency; the README quickstart leads with it; `add`\n  cross-references it.\n- `diff`, `links`, `tree` `--help` examples show the no-id most-recent form,\n  matching `show` and `log` (consistency fix for review finding O1).\n\n**Non-goals**\n\n- No change to command semantics, flags, JSON output shapes, or the\n  `add`/`ingest` split.\n- No `add`/`ingest` merge, no `add --file`, no file-binding flag, no entry\n  \"sync\" attribute, no `reconcile` command — all deferred to §6's separate spec.\n\n## 3. Changes\n\n### 3.1 `CRANKY_PROMPT.md` — good-CLI-defaults checks\n\nAppend a new bullet cluster after the existing \"CLI norm violations to keep an\neye out for\" list (currently ends ~line 291), under a heading such as\n**\"Default \u0026 guidance ergonomics.\"** Each item is phrased as a finding:\n\n1. A command needing a positional arg fails with a bare framework message\n   (`accepts 1 arg(s), received 0`) instead of saying *what* is missing, *how*\n   to find a valid value, and a *worked example*.\n2. A read-only/inspection command refuses to run with no argument when there is\n   an obvious safe default (the most-recently-touched object), forcing the user\n   to copy-paste an id they just saw.\n3. A *mutating or destructive* command silently guesses a target from a default.\n   A default that changes state is a footgun; guessing belongs only on\n   read-only paths.\n4. An inferred-default notice is printed to **stdout** (polluting pipes and\n   `--json`) instead of **stderr**, or is not suppressed in machine-output mode.\n5. A leaf command's `--help` shows usage/flags but no *worked, annotated\n   example* of a real invocation.\n6. The example in an error message and the example in `--help` are maintained as\n   two separate copies and have drifted apart.\n7. **One concept, one verb.** The same gesture means two different contracts in\n   different places (e.g., \"give it a file\" is a one-shot snapshot here but a\n   living, mutate-the-file sync there), or a single verb is reused for unrelated\n   meanings (e.g., \"sync\" meaning both push-to-remote and mirror-a-local-file).\n8. The tool's **headline / 90% workflow is not obvious**: a newcomer reading\n   `--help` or the top of the README cannot tell which command is the common\n   path versus the manual/escape-hatch one.\n\n### 3.2 `ingest` as the headline (`cmd/kref/commands.go`)\n\nReplace the `ingest` `Example` block so it walks the standard workflow and\nteaches idempotency:\n\n```\nkref ingest docs/notes.md   # one file (writes a kref-id trailer back into it)\nkref ingest docs/           # a whole directory tree\nkref ingest .               # everything under the cwd\nkref ingest docs/notes.md   # re-run is idempotent: unchanged = no-op, edited = update\n```\n\n### 3.3 `add` cross-references `ingest` (`cmd/kref/commands.go`)\n\n`add` gains a `Long` (it has none today); its `Example` block is unchanged:\n\n\u003e Compose a single entry from flags. To create entries from existing markdown\n\u003e files or directories, use `kref ingest`.\n\n### 3.4 Read-only default examples (`cmd/kref/commands.go`)\n\n`diff`, `links`, and `tree` each gain a no-id example line in their `Example`\nblock, mirroring the form already present on `show` (`commands.go:344`) and\n`log` (`commands.go:1100`), e.g.:\n\n```\nkref diff                 # the most-recently-modified entry\n```\n\n### 3.5 README quickstart (`README.md`)\n\nLead the Quickstart with the ingest path as the 90% workflow, and mention the\nkeep-in-sync loop (`kref hooks install`). Keep the edit minimal and additive.\n\n## 4. Testing\n\nMost changes are help/doc text, so testing leans on the existing ginkgo suites:\n\n- The existing `cmd/kref` test \"every runnable leaf command carries an `Example`\n  block\" continues to pass unchanged.\n- Extend the help-completeness suite (`cmd/kref/cli_test.go`):\n  - assert `kref diff --help`, `kref links --help`, `kref tree --help` each\n    contain the no-id most-recent example line;\n  - assert `kref add --help` contains the `ingest` cross-reference text.\n- No automated test for `CRANKY_PROMPT.md` or `README.md` (prose).\n- `add`'s new `Long` is descriptive only; no behavior test is warranted.\n\n## 5. Risks \u0026 mitigations\n\n- **Example/doc drift.** Commands without an `argGuide` keep hand-maintained\n  examples; mitigated by the help-completeness assertions in §4.\n- **README churn vs. other in-flight branches.** Keep the quickstart edit small\n  and additive to minimize conflicts.\n- **Checklist bloat.** Keep the CRANKY cluster to the eight earned checks; no\n  padding.\n\n## 6. Deferred (separate spec)\n\nA per-entry, **local-only** tracking attribute plus a `kref reconcile` that\nwalks tracked entries and reconciles them with their source files. Its central\nopen question is the machine-local-path-vs-shared-entry tension noted in §1.\nThis is a non-trivial feature and gets its own brainstorm → spec → plan cycle;\nit is explicitly out of scope here."}]}